    <edge source=" But the needle on the gauge did not quiver. Nothing indicated the presence of a ship. But the evidence of his eyes was incontestable.&#10; &#10; Or was it? Doubt gripped him. Did the loneliness of all these years in space twist his mind till he was imagining the appearance of faint ghost-like rocket ships?&#10; &#10; The thought shot through his mind like a thunder bolt. Ghost Ship! Was this the thing that Dobbin had seen before he died? But that was impossible. Ghost Ships existed nowhere but in legends and tall tales told by men drunk with the liquors of Mars.&#10; &#10; &quot;There is no ship there. There is no ship there,&quot; Willard told himself over and over again as he looked at the vague outline of the ship, now motionless a few hundred miles away.&#10; &#10; Deep within him a faint voice cried, &quot; It's come—for me! &quot; but Willard stilled it. This was no fantasy. There was a scientific reason for it. There must be! Or should there be? Throughout all Earth history there had been Ghost Ships sailing the Seven Seas—ships doomed to roam forever because their crew broke some unbreakable law. If this was true for the ships of the" target="The mysterious apparition that old Willard initially thought was the Ghost Ship is a life and blood rocket ship from Earth. The ghost-like quality he remembered seeing in the Ghost Ship from his past doesn't apply to this ship, as it shines with starlight and has solid lines, windows, and vents. However, due to his long years of solitude and earlier experiences, Willard questions his sanity and fears that the Ghost Ship might still be near. This fear makes him unsure if what he's seeing is real or just an illusion.&#10;&#10;The source of the happy message that brings Willard to tears is a space-telegrapher on the real rocket ship from Earth. They establish communication with Willard, who sends an answering message filled with joy and gratitude. However, due to his outdated sensors and long isolation, 