    <edge source=" meaning. About three years must have passed since his last record in the log book of the Mary Lou . At that time, he remembered, he suffered another great disappointment. On the port side there suddenly appeared a full-sized rocket ship. For many minutes Willard was half-mad with joy thinking that a passing ship was ready to rescue him. But the joy was short-lived, for the rocket ship abruptly turned away and slowly disappeared. As Willard watched it go away he saw the light of a distant star through the space ship. A heart-breaking agony fell upon him. It was not a ship from Earth. It was the Ghost Ship, mocking him.&#10; &#10; Since then Willard did not look out the window of his craft. A vague fear troubled him that perhaps the Ghost Ship might be here, waiting and watching, and that he would go mad if he saw it.&#10; &#10; How many years passed he could not tell. But this he knew. He was no longer a young man. Perhaps fifteen years has disappeared into nothing. Perhaps twenty. He did not know and he did not care.&#10; &#10; &#10;&#10; &#10; Willard awoke from a deep sleep and prepared his bed. He did it, not because it was necessary," target="1. Three years before the events of the story, Willard had a significant encounter that affected him deeply. He saw what he believed to be a Ghost Ship on the port side of the Mary Lou. The ship appeared for a while, sparking hope in Willard that he might be rescued, but it abruptly turned away and disappeared, leaving him with a crushing sense of disappointment.&#10;2. This experience with the supposed Ghost Ship, combined with his long years of solitude, caused Willard to question his own sanity. He began to fear that the Ghost Ship might still be near, waiting and watching, and that seeing it would drive him mad. As a result, he avoided looking out of the window of his craft.&#10;3. The story doesn't provide specific dates or time frames beyond Willard's recollection of his last log book entry being three years prior to the events of the story. Therefore, we cannot determine the exact sequence of events or how much time elapsed between different experiences in Willard's past.">
