    <edge source="The mysterious, half-invisible object that Willard observes heading toward the Mary Lou is a Ghost Ship, an old-fashioned rocket ship that has been drifting in space for many years. It appears faint and ghost-like because its mass and energy have gradually been drained over time, making it almost invisible to Earth ships. The crew of this Ghost Ship is likely unaware of their changed state, as they remain real to themselves but not to other ships that have not been in space for more than fifteen years. This is why Willard's instruments do not detect the ship's presence, even though his eyes can see its vague outline." target="1. The Space Ship Mary Lou's disappearance signifies the fate of spaceships that wander alone in space for extended periods. Over time, they become drained of their mass and energy until nothing is left but a vague outline in space. This phenomenon is explained by the theory that matter is relative, and something real under one condition can be non-real under another. To ships from Earth that have not been in space for more than fifteen years, these Ghost Ships do not exist.&#10;2. John Willard, the lone survivor of the Mary Lou, copes with his solitude during the expedition by clinging to memories of his life on Earth. Each night, he dreams of walking the streets of Arden and feeling the natural elements under his feet. He also engages in activities that maintain a sense of normality, such as keeping time and preparing his bed even though it is not necessary in space.&#10;3. Willard's fear of the Ghost Ship is rooted in its initial appearance, which brought him both joy and despair when he thought it was a passing ship ready to rescue him, only for it to turn away and disappear. This experience amplifies his loneliness, leading him to avoid looking out of the window of his craft to prevent going mad if he sees the Ghost Ship again.&#10;4. Willard's encounter with the Captain of another Ghost Ship provides a shocking revelation: they too are gradually draining of mass and energy until they become invisible to Earth ships. In essence, they have become Ghost Ships sailing the Seven Seas, destined to roam forever due to their transgression of unbreakable laws.&#10;5. Willard's initial reaction to seeing the Ghost Ship turn back is a mix of fear and longing, as it represents his only connection to something real from Earth, and when it vanishes, he is once again left alone with the dreaded loneliness of the stars.">
