    <edge source="The mysterious, half-invisible object that Willard observes heading toward the Mary Lou is a Ghost Ship, an old-fashioned rocket ship that has been drifting in space for many years. It appears faint and ghost-like because its mass and energy have gradually been drained over time, making it almost invisible to Earth ships. The crew of this Ghost Ship is likely unaware of their changed state, as they remain real to themselves but not to other ships that have not been in space for more than fifteen years. This is why Willard's instruments do not detect the ship's presence, even though his eyes can see its vague outline." target="Since the death of his best friend Harry Dobbin, Willard has spent the last two years alone on the damaged spaceship Mary Lou. With limited resources, he has managed to survive, but the isolation and solitude have taken a toll on him. He has been drifting through space for over thirteen years, unable to return to Earth due to his altered state as &quot;ghosts,&quot; making them invisible to ships that have not been in space for more than fifteen years.&#10;&#10;During this time, Willard has clung to the hope of being rescued and returning to Earth. He had a shared hallucination with Dobbin of seeing a Ghost Ship before Dobbin's death, which further contributes to his fear and questioning of his sanity. The anguish and isolation have been significant, but he continues to hold on to the memories of his life on Earth.&#10;&#10;Recently, Willard received news that he has been rescued and is invited to come aboard an Earth-ship, representing a symbol of life, connection, and normalcy that he has longed for after spending decades in isolation and solitude. However, he learns that the Mary Lou and its crew have been drifting through space for so long that they have passed beyond the boundaries of known space and can no longer return to Earth, further reinforcing his fear and loneliness.&#10;&#10;In summary, over the last two years, Willard has continued to survive in isolation aboard the damaged Mary Lou, experiencing increasing loneliness and despair, but still clinging to hope and memories of his life on Earth.">
