ing to Earth is the prospect of being rescued by an Earth-ship. In the story, it is mentioned that Willard receives the joyful news that he has been rescued and is invited to come aboard an Earth-ship. This news is particularly meaningful to him because for many years, he had been alone in space aboard the disabled Mary Lou, with only the hope of being rescued and returned to Earth keeping him alive. However, Dobbin passed away during the journey, further adding to Willard's loneliness and despair. The newspaper article published seven years after their departure briefly mentions that the Mary Lou was last heard from thirteen years ago, indicating that there has been no contact with the ship or its crew since then. It is likely that the Space Ship Mary Lou and its crew continue to drift through space as &quot;ghosts,&quot; unable to return home and facing an uncertain future.">
